    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.38"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">38</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>August 12, 1972</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>On Sunday, August 6, I viewed for the first time your interview with Dick Cavett. Having missed the two previous telecasts, I was delighted to learn that <hi rend="caps">ETV</hi> was re-running the program. After having now watched and listened to the interview, I feel the need to write you and express my personal appreciation.</p> 
                
                <p>As you well know, it is sometimes difficult to find appropriate words to adequately convey one's sentiments after witnessing a particular event. I find this to be true at this time as I try to write you of my impressions of your interview. Nevertheless, I do want to say seeing the program was an extremely rewarding experience. I had read some of your works prior to this time and found them immensely interesting and enjoyable. However, hearing you recite from them offered a new dimension that I thought did not exist. I now intend to re-read them with an eye and ear tuned to the intrinsic lyrical eloquence which this literature seems to contain.</p> 
                
                <p>I guess what I want most is to simply offer you a sincere Thank You. A Thank You for the literature and poetry which you have written and continue to write; and most of all a Thank You for the contribution which you are making to my personal and intellectual growth.</p>
                
                <p>This fall I am beginning a graduate program in Native American Literature at the University of Nebraska. Thus, I intend to make a career of attempting to understand the immense resources present in Indian literature and the history and literature of Nebraska and the Plains. I am sure your work will be of significance in whatever success I have in attaining this goal.</p> 
                
                <p>If you ever find that your schedule would permit a few
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.39"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">39</fw>
                
                    spare moments, I would consider it an honor to meet with you and share some of the questions and thoughts I have about your works and about Nebraska and Indian history.</p> 
                
                <p>Once again Thank You.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>In Appreciation,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Brent A. Warren</signed>
                    <signed>Brent A. Warren</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
